Since you are trying to mock &#39;dqCntlWfDefnTyp&#39; in your test class and the object itself is being instantiated in the class that you are trying to test, you inevitably run into some issues. The primary problem is that the object cannot be mocked because it is being recreated in during the test.

There are a few options, but the best choice in my humble opinion is using [PowerMockito][1]. You will be able to replace the object within the class that is being tested with the one you mock.


An excellent example of this usage of PowerMockito from @raspacorp on this [question][2]:

    public class MyClass {
    void method1{
        MyObject obj1=new MyObject();
        obj1.method1();
    }
    }


And the test class...

    @RunWith(PowerMockRunner.class)
    @PrepareForTest(MyClass.class)
    public class MyClassTest {
    @Test
    public void testMethod1() {      
        MyObject myObjectMock = mock(MyObject.class);
        when(myObjectMock.method1()).thenReturn(&lt;whatever you want to return&gt;);   
        PowerMockito.whenNew(MyObject.class).withNoArguments().thenReturn(myObjectMock);

        MyClass objectTested = new MyClass();
        objectTested.method1();

        ... // your assertions or verification here 
    }
    }

  [1]: https://github.com/jayway/powermock/wiki
  [2]: https://stackoverflow.com/a/30633175/4930850

